Path: godot/getting_started/first_3d_game/08.score_and_replay.rst
Summary: This section covers adding a score display, UI elements, and basic theme overrides for a Godot game.

Add a Control node named "UserInterface" as a child of the "Main" node.
Add a Label node named "ScoreLabel" as a child of "UserInterface".
In the Inspector, set the Text property of ScoreLabel to "Score: 0".
To change the font color, go to the Theme Overrides section in the Inspector, expand Colors, and enable Font Color. Set the font color to black.
Position the ScoreLabel in the viewport by clicking and dragging it away from the top-left corner.
The UserInterface node is used to group UI elements and apply themes.
---CHUNK---
Document: First 3D Game Tutorial
Path: godot/getting_started/first_3d_game/08.score_and_replay.rst
Summary: This section explains how to create and customize a UI theme for the game, focusing on setting default font and font size.
Creating a UI theme
Select the UserInterface node. In the Inspector, create a new theme resource in Theme -> Theme.
Click on the theme resource to open the theme editor in the bottom panel. This panel shows a preview of how built-in UI widgets will appear with the current theme resource.
By default, a theme has the following properties: Default Base Scale, Default Font, and Default Font Size.
You can add more properties to the theme resource for designing complex user interfaces. For more information on creating and editing themes, see the documentation on GUI skinning.
The Default Font property accepts a font file, such as TTF or OTF formats.
In the FileSystem dock, expand the fonts directory. Drag and drop the Montserrat-Medium.ttf file from the project onto the Default Font property in the theme editor. The text in the preview will update.
To increase the text size, set the Default Font Size property to 22 pixels.
---CHUNK---
